TITLE Early Length CF Array Comparisons
EARLY LENGTH CF ARRAY COMPARISONS
When comparing arrays with expensive operations (sorting, deep equality, serialization), check lengths first. If lengths differ, the arrays cannot be equal. 
In real-world applications, this optimization is especially valuable when the comparison runs in hot paths (event handlers, render loops). 
Incorrect (always runs expensive comparison): 
CODE typescript 175CHARS
Two O(n log n) sorts run even when current.length is 5 and original.length is 100. There is also overHO joining the arrays and comparing the strings. 
Correct (O(1) length check first): 
CODE typescript 429CHARS
This new approach is more efficient because: 
It avoids the overHO sorting and joining the arrays when lengths differ It avoids consuming memory for the joined strings (especially important for large arrays) It avoids mutating the original arrays It returns early when a difference is found 